{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"alias":"unlighted-roselike-tsetsefly","description":"## Why\nExisting installs need an explicit, discoverable heal trigger that respects the git-fsck\n(read-only) vs git-maintenance (mutating) convention, plus the server boot path should\nconverge. Plain fsck must stay read-only; healing is opt-in until the doctor epic lands.\n\n## What\nAdd `--fix` to `rebar fsck`: default `fsck` is read-only and REPORTS an `ensures: N/M applied`\nline (honors `no_mutate`, preserves byte-parity in the converged case); `fsck --fix` runs\n`run_ensures()` and heals. Wire MCP server startup (`mcp_server.main`, after the --help check)\nto run `run_ensures()` so a booting server converges. Update fsck byte-parity tests for the\nnew report line.\n\n## Scope\nIn: `fsck --fix` flag, the report line, no_mutate gating, server-startup wiring, byte-parity\ntest updates. Out: the registry (WS1), the write-path hint (WS2).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Plain `rebar fsck` mutates nothing new and prints an `ensures: N/M applied` line; `--no_mutate` surfaces run it read-only\n- [ ] `rebar fsck --fix` runs `run_ensures()` and is git-level idempotent: two `--fix` runs on a converged store produce zero new commits/pushes\n- [ ] MCP server startup runs `run_ensures()` after the --help check (a booted server is converged)\n- [ ] fsck byte-parity tests updated; converged store → fsck output unchanged apart from the new report line","id":"424c-c66a-a5c0-49ab","parent_id":"9ccb-27ee-24dd-4944","priority":2,"tags":[],"ticket_type":"story","title":"WS3: rebar fsck --fix (read-only default, reports ensures: N/M) + MCP server-startup wiring"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1783569042661166001,"uuid":"7f4b32dd-c3e4-495f-8bce-09cf0e16b0a2"}